         <h1>Anselmo Colzani, 87, Baritone Who Was a Fixture at the Met </h1>
           <div class="row">
               <div class="col-md-10">
 					<p class="text-left">
<blue>1</blue>Anselmo Colzani , an operatic baritone whose dramatic sensibility helped make him a fixture at the Metropolitan Opera and other houses in the 1950 's and 1960 's , died on Sunday at a nursing home in Milan . <br><blue>2</blue>He was 87 . <br><blue>3</blue>He died after a long illness , Marina Boagno , president of the Franco Corelli Opera Association , told the Italian news media . <br><blue>4</blue>Mr. Colzani was one of several Italian baritones who made their Met debuts in the 1960 season , after the sudden death of Leonard Warren onstage during '' La Forza del Destino '' in March . <br><blue>5</blue>A few weeks later , Mr. Colzani took over Mr. Warren 's role in Verdi 's '' Simone Boccanegra . '' <br><blue>6</blue>It was not only the first time he had ever sung at the Met , but the first time he had ever sung the role ; he had to learn it in a matter of days . <br><blue>7</blue>He acquitted himself well enough that he became a regular at the Met for the next 18 seasons . <br><blue>8</blue>Particular signature roles included Jack Rance in Puccini 's '' Fanciulla del West '' and the title role of Verdi 's '' Falstaff , '' as well as Scarpia in '' Tosca , '' Amonasro in '' Aida '' and Iago in '' Otello . '' <br><blue>9</blue>Born on March 28 , 1918 , in Budrio , near Bologna , Italy , to musical parents , Anselmo Colzani joined the Italian Army before beginning to study singing in earnest . <br><blue>10</blue>He made his debut at the Teatro Comunale in Bologna in 1946 in the small role of the Herald in Wagner 's '' Lohengrin , '' appearing with a soprano making her debut at the house , Renata Tebaldi . <br><blue>11</blue>There followed the title role of '' Rigoletto , '' which helped start his career . <br><blue>12</blue>In 1952 , he made his debut at La Scala in '' Cavalleria Rusticana . '' <br><blue>13</blue>He made his debut at the San Francisco Opera in 1956 and sang there a number of times , but it was at the Met that he established his most lasting foothold in the United States . <br><blue>14</blue>He appeared there and throughout Europe with the major stars of the day , including Maria Callas , Galina Vishnevskaya , Zinka Milanov , Franco Corelli , Richard Tucker and Carlo Bergonzi . <br><blue>15</blue>His broad repertory also included new and less-known works like Darius Milhaud 's '' David '' and Ildebrando Pizzetti 's '' Fedra . '' <br><blue>16</blue>Mr. Colzani 's last Met performance was as Michonnet in '' Adriana Lecouvreur '' in 1978 . <br><blue>17</blue>He continued singing until 1980 , when he gave his final performance in '' Tosca . '' <br><blue>18</blue>His hometown , Budrio , recently established an international opera competition named for him , which was held for the fourth time in February . <br><blue>19</blue>Mr. Colzani 's first wife died young , leaving him with two daughters , Bianca and Miriam . <br><blue>20</blue>They survive him , as does his second wife , Ada , to whom he was married for more than 50 years . <br><hr><br><blue>1(3)</blue>: <m_str>Mr. Warren 's role in Verdi 's</m_str> (5_10) 	<m_str>it</m_str> (6_31) 	<m_str>the role</m_str> (6_24) 	<br><blue>2(34)</blue>: <m_str>His</m_str> (15_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (18_14) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_27) 	<m_str>Mr. Colzani 's</m_str> (19_1) 	<m_str>Mr. Colzani</m_str> (4_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (11_14) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (19_10) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (12_4) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (12_6) 	<m_str>Mr. Colzani 's</m_str> (16_1) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (20_3) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (20_7) 	<m_str>Mr. Colzani</m_str> (5_6) 	<m_str>him</m_str> (1_12) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (13_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (13_3) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (17_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (2_1) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (20_15) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (17_8) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (10_1) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (17_10) 	<m_str>his</m_str> (10_3) 	<m_str>he</m_str> (6_8) 	<m_str>Anselmo Colzani</m_str> (9_20) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (14_1) 	<m_str>His</m_str> (18_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (3_1) 	<m_str>He</m_str> (7_1) 	<m_str